{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505347","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505347"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:29:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:29:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2432"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2432","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2432"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.37,0.17,0.29,0.08,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2432"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"39282"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2432","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2432"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2432"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"23601"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3005"},{"type":"tags","id":"4183"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1868"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2640"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3181"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9762"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15418"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38495"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"39282","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/39282"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents with a one month history of intermittent painless passage of blood in his urine. He has no other urinary symptoms. His medical history includes gastro-oesophageal reflux disease and asthma. He takes esomeprazole and uses a ventolin puffer. He has a 50 pack-year smoking history and drink 14 standard drinks per week.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPhysical examination, including digital rectal examination, is unremarkable. Cystoscopy shows a 3 cm papillary tumour on the dome of the bladder, and a transurethral resection is performed. Histopathology shows a low grade, non-muscle-invasive transitional cell carcinoma. There is no evidence of metastatic disease on CT chest/abdo/pelvis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate single intervention?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cystoscopy in 3 months","External beam pelvic radiotherapy","Intravesical BCG","Intravesical docetaxel","Radical cystectomy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBladder transitional cell carcinoma (TCC, also called urothelial carcinoma or UC) is the most common urinary malignancy. First-line treatment of superficial UCs is via transurethral resection, which also allows for histopathological grading of the tumour. In a low grade, non-muscle-invasive tumour, a repeat \u003Cstrong\u003Ecystoscopy in 3 months\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate treatment option.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELow grade superficial urothelial cancer (low risk) is managed with trans urethral resection of bladder tumour alone. For recurrent, high grade superficial urothelial cancer, a single dose of intravesical mitomycin or epirubicin is used. This is ordered in advance and is administered in theatre, and managed with cytotoxic precautions in recovery. It is never used with a first diagnosed bladder cancer, as is described in this case. For the first resection, deep samples are taken to ensure detrusor muscle is in the specimen and the patient can be adequately staged histologically. Because of this deep wound, intravesical therapies are avoided due to the risk of systemic absorption of the agents. The chemotherapy drugs are meant to dwell in the bladder to kill any floating cancer cells, and not act systemically. Docetaxel is never used for this purpose.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravesical BCG\u003C/strong\u003E immunotherapy is used for high grade non-muscle-invasive tumours to prevent or delay recurrence. It is not routinely used in low grade UCs as these tumours do not respond as well to BCG immunotherapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravesical docetaxel\u003C/strong\u003E is a second-line treatment for high-risk cancers which fail to respond to intravesical BCG. Mitomycin is typically the first-line intravesical chemotherapeutic option of choice, administered intraoperatively during the initial resection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadical cystectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is the gold standard treatment for muscle-invasive UCs, however is not warranted in non-muscle-invasive UC due to the efficacy of transurethral resection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExternal beam pelvic radiotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E is a bladder-conserving option for treatment of invasive tumours, however it is not recommended for a simple superficial tumour due to the significant risk of side effects and the efficacy of simple resection in these tumours.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe prognosis for bladder UC is typically very good, however there is a significant rate of recurrence even with complete resection.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Complete transurethral resection (+/- intravesical mitomycin) is the first-line management for low-risk urothelial carcinoma."],"references":["Babjuk M, B\u00f6hle A, Burger M, Capoun O, Cohen D, Comp\u00e9rat EM, Hern\u00e1ndez V, Kaasinen E, Palou J, Roupr\u00eat M, van Rhijn BWG, Shariat SF, Soukup V, Sylvester RJ, Zigeuner R. EAU Guidelines on Non-Muscle-invasive Urothelial Carcinoma of the Bladder: Update 2016. Eur Urol. 2017 Mar;71(3):447-461. doi: 10.1016/j.eururo.2016.05.041. Epub 2016 Jun 17. PMID: 27324428.","Comperat E, Amin MB, Cathomas R, et al. Current best practice for bladder cancer: a narrative review of diagnostics and treatments. Lancet. 2022; 400:1712-21."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"23601"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2432"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"23601","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/23601"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-09-08T21:19:28+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-14T07:44:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2432"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"39282"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationshi